<p>You bring up some good points here which I'll address down below. But first, to clarify the parameters of 'Paradise':<br />
<span style="text-decoration: line-through;">A place free of suffering and pain. Long life is all but guaranteed and there are no responsibilities (everything we need, like technology and infrastructure) is already there. This is a permanent decision though, as you can't get back through the gateway once you enter.<br />
Am considering whether or not this could be parallel Earth opened by people seeking a better life, or a trick by another anomaly to gather humans for food or something else.</span> <em>Due to revisions, this is no longer the case. See summary above for accurate info.</em></p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Open&nbsp;Responses?&nbsp;+</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Close&nbsp;-</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p><span style="font-size:large;">Point 1 - No Ethical Dilemma nor Containment Issues:</span></p>
<p>Ok, but how about this:<br />
Paradise is open, free, and able to fit everyone. However, the Foundation, naturally doubtful about an offer that seems to good to be true, don't know whether this is actually Paradise or not. Thus, the Ethics Committee has a dilemma: to send everyone in there or not? By choosing to send people, the Foundation is either freeing the human race from suffering and pain forever, or sentencing them to death or something worse. Neither can be confirmed, as all technology malfunctions and stops working once it enters the gateway, and people don't come back.</p>
<p>Containment is marginally less important, as all the Foundation must do is bar off the area and do what they usually do, prevent any information about the place getting out.</p>
<p><span style="font-size:large;">Point 2 - Out-of-place Elements:</span></p>
<p>I am considering replacing the guardian with a memetic effect, that being that anyone who sees the gateway instantly knows what lies behind it (Paradise and the properties thereof). I hesitate because this may be viewed as cliche by other members of this Site, what do you think?</p>
<p>The fake iteration was placed for an in-Foundation-universe reason, namely, to act as a decoy and deter anyone trying to poke into places they weren't supposed to. However, it could simply be rendered obsolete by a warning at the top of the document that promises severe consequences for anyone accessing it without proper authorisation, as well as a memetic kill agent for additional protection.</p>
<p><span style="font-size:large;">Point 3 - Discovery:</span></p>
<p>So I was thinking about this one for a while, and I came up with this.<br />
Very small coastal town somewhere (information would be redacted of course), close to a small beach. Paradise gateway appears, changes the beach entirely. A couple of people visit, are amazed, see the Paradise gateway and promptly enter it.<br />
The Foundation gets strange missing person reports from that town as well as sightings of flora and fauna never seen before on Earth and decides to investigate. They find the beach and the Paradise gateway, make up explanations for the missing people, amnesticize the population of what they saw recently, and cordon off the area for 'dangerous animals' or something similar.<br />
Does that work?</p>
<hr /></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Close&nbsp;-</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Anyway, that's about it for my responses. Thank you for this crit, and hopefully what I've come up with is a suitable explanation for your concerns!</p>
<p><span style="font-size:x-small;">P.S My gratitude for you coming to crit me right after being sick for a while</span></p>

