<p>You make good points here, which I'll try to address (again):</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Open</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Close</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>I don't think this fundamentally addresses the critique that I was giving, that the Foundation wouldn't be uniquely challenged by this.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>So I have a possible solution for this, if we bring back the concept of limited space:<br />
Have this SCP is set either in a canon where the world is becoming uninhabitable (e.g End of Death, Competitive Eschatology, Ad Astra Per Aspera, etc.), or have there be an impeding or current disaster of some sort when this SCP is discovered (or after it is discovered). With the limited space problem coupled with the problems humanity is facing, this SCP could function as an escape but also an ethical dilemma (who's staying and who's going?). As such, the Foundation must undergo serious thinking over whether the use of this <em>at all</em> is ethical, as it would mean leaving people behind.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>If all they've got is a compulsive voice in their heads telling them it's Paradise, but people don't leave, then they'd contain it and that's the end of the story. Additionally, how is it paradise if people can't leave? Seems like a property you're just adding to make things more difficult.<br />
I would recommend against that. A sort of &quot;info drop&quot; like that is something I've only ever seen work in SCP-5471. Is there a reason you can't just have the Foundation infer everything via experimentation?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Good points again. I think I'll remove that property, as it's kind of janky in regards to the anomaly (just functions as some barrier to make things more difficult, as you said).<br />
I'll also remove the 'info drop' part of it, instead making it able to be freely explored (basically, it's a larger version of the beach, but with a couple of different biomes). It's quite small though, and there'll probably be some sort of 'end' to the pocket dimension.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>That's about it for the second round of responses. Hopefully they're adequate!</p>

