<p>My main concern here is that the anomaly lessens your emotional plot beats. As far as I can tell, the dramatic core of your story rests on the debate between the two protagonists about what to do regarding ‘the end of the world’. To pivot at the end and reveal that the escape they were arguing about is just another manipulative anomaly that’s using their argument to take over the world feels like it would negate any points made previously, weakening both your ending and your emotional narrative in retrospect. How do you plan to avoid that?</p>
<p>Besides that, I should mention that I’m rather confused as to how most of this would be documented in clinical tone. To the best of my knowledge, folks scrambling to survive an apocalypse or hypnotized by plants might not keep up to date on their documentation.</p>
