<p>Hey again, thanks for the crit!<br />
Sorry for the delayed response, an unfortunate cmd+r set me back after I had formulated most of my reply (along with other things). But anyway&#8230;</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Here&nbsp;are&nbsp;my&nbsp;responses!</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Woooooosh</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>First things first, the easier part of your crit to answer.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Besides that, I should mention that I’m rather confused as to how most of this would be documented in clinical tone. To the best of my knowledge, folks scrambling to survive an apocalypse or hypnotized by plants might not keep up to date on their documentation.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Well, most of this will be documented through emails, site memos, chat logs, security footage, etc, instead of official documentation. In case you're wondering how the sense of mystery would be preserved with security footage, it'll be mostly obscured by leaves and the like (the plants would grow on the ceiling for stealth).</p>
<p>And now the second part.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>My main concern here is that the anomaly lessens your emotional plot beats. [&#8230;] How do you plan to avoid that?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>By building off of P1 (the protagonist against evacuating) being incarcerated in their cell, and thus avoiding P2's (the protagonist for evacuating) speech and exodus of the town into the gateway<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-306623-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-306623-1')">1</a></sup>, I plan to create an entirely new ethical dilemma that builds off of the first.<br />
The story goes:<br />
- P1, taking a USB full of the contents of their computer, escapes the town and is rescued by Foundation personnel<br />
- They're understandably traumatised and tormented by survivor's guilt, and develop PTSD and depression<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-306623-2" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-306623-2')">2</a></sup>. This is revealed in a psychological evaluation<br />
- However, the Foundation begins to suspect something is wrong after P1 suffers numerous seizures, bouts of uncharacteristic and extremely erratic behaviour, and eventually, a hemorrhagic stroke (note that they are the only person the Foundation has in custody who has had contact with the anomaly)<br />
- Blood tests reveal the presence of anomalous prions within P1's brain. Through extensive testing, these prions are found to be thaumaturgically charged and, through a poorly understood mechanism, partially 'link' P1's mind to the large, central hive mind I mentioned in my summary<br />
- Said hive mind uses the prions to both communicate with and physically damage (haemorrhage) P1, for the purpose of convincing them to return to the gateway, in exchange for P2 and the numerous other people it had taken (revealed in another interview)<br />
- Through the interview, the Foundation finds out that 1) The prions appear through a chemical/thaumic reaction after ingesting the hallucinogen, 2) the anomaly feeds off of brain activity and converts it to energy (this process creates huge amounts of energy) using the prions as a transfer mechanism, 3) everyone considered lost to the anomaly is in fact alive (but in a vegetative state), and 4) P1 is their only method of communicating with/discreetly spying upon the anomaly<br />
- Point 4 is true because testing with others has only resulted in the participants immediately succumbing to brain haemorrhage (the anomaly finds no point in keeping them alive as it cannot bargain with them)<br />
- As such, their only option of neutralising the anomaly is to find out its weakness through P1 with subtle memetic influence, while keeping them (and thus the hive mind) completely oblivious to the Foundation's true goal. Unfortunately, this means constantly reinjecting them with prions to keep the connection stable, making their mental suffering much worse<br />
- As the 05 Council deems the Ethics Committee emotionally compromised by the circumstances (P1 was their friend, and their judgement would be affected by that), they decide to come to a decision on their own, and, after much deliberation, the motion passes that P1 should be used as a method of spying (Operation: Verdant Sleeper)<br />
- Article ends with the message that the operation is in effect, results pending</p>
<hr />
<p>My main concern is that this may not in fact solve the original problem (lessens emotional impact) rather than add something else entirely. Hopefully not though.<br />
Also, the anomaly wants P1 (and P1 only) because it finds their thoughts incredibly tasty (extreme grief and guilt stemming from the anomaly itself &#8212;&gt; yummy). This is documented in P1's journal, which is covertly read when they are asleep. Breach of privacy I know, but this is for the sake of the world.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<br />
Anyway, that's it for my response ('twas a big one, I know, sorry about that). Thanks for reading, and hope this assuages your concerns!
