<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>I think the disaster that forces the Foundation to shove people into an idyllic pocket dimension feels contrived. It feels like there needed to be a reason to shove people in there, so a disaster scenario was thought up to put them on there. The reveal that it was actually a spirit luring people into a trap also&#8230;kinda doesn't impress me either. Maybe I'm just cynical, but the idea of 'paradise actually is trap' doesn't feel particularly original to me.</p>
<p>I did read the other crits here, by the way.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>If you want my take, I suggest you set up a fleshed-out protagonist and antagonist to argue over the space problem, weaving that into a more general exploration of Paradise's lore, and then end with a type of subversion or reveal.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I can what see what you're trying to do here, mind you. I like what you're going for, but again, disaster feels forced and the nature spirit thing doesn't impress me.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>change the beach into basically a spreading land virus</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I had a crazy idea just now&#8230;what if you expand on this bit?</p>
<p>What if these 'disasters' were pre-constructed by the paradise land itself to entice people to come in and people walks right into the trap, hook, line, and sinker?</p>
<p>Just my hot take, of course. Anywho, I hope I helped and I bid you good luck and good day. 👍👍👍</p>
