<p>Hey there again, thanks for the recrit!<br />
You bring up a good point, so here is my (quite long, admittedly. Sorry about the wall of text!) response:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Open&nbsp;Response&nbsp;+</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Woooooooosh</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>So you tell me here that the whole thing feels a bit contrived for your liking (with the whole disaster thing and the gateway being a false solution):</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I think the disaster that forces the Foundation to shove people into an idyllic pocket dimension feels contrived. It feels like there needed to be a reason to shove people in there, so a disaster scenario was thought up to put them on there.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Looking back on it, the concept does come off as a little bit&#8230; forced. However, you also provide a possible solution:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>What if these 'disasters' were pre-constructed by the paradise land itself to entice people to come in and people walks right into the trap, hook, line, and sinker?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Interesting. I've thought about this for a while, and I might have just the thing for that.</p>
<p>I established that there are native flora and fauna in and around Paradise (both the shores and the actual pocket dimension), and that they are all universally docile. But what if the Foundation has underestimated them?</p>
<p>It starts off with the spirit (I know you're unimpressed by the spirit, but I haven't thought of a replacement yet) creating a couple of large, strong animals capable of breaching containment (as a placeholder, think something like a rhino) that are still quite docile. The Foundation finds these, almost has a containment breach or two, logs them, and is now wary. But then no more appear, and the Foundation relaxes.</p>
<p>This isn't the end though. A much more devious and subtle way of breaching containment comes in the form of small, parasitic, plant organisms that possess a powerful anomalous hallucinogen that can completely alter what a person sees. They are quite weak at first, and their stores of hallucinogen only last three days before they run out and die. However, they breed quickly, and they rapidly infest everyone on the local containment Site before setting up a large nest (no one can see it because they are all under the influence of the hallucinogen) to keep everyone permanently infested. Arriving personnel succumb as well, but they're only temporarily infested (just to make sure they don't see anything).</p>
<hr /></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Open&nbsp;Response&nbsp;II:&nbsp;Electric&nbsp;Boogaloo&nbsp;+</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">This&nbsp;is&nbsp;the&nbsp;narrative</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>Anyway, both the protagonists are present on the Site (and thus infested) when they both see (in actuality, this is a hallucination) an email from the 05 Council notifying them of multiple catastrophic Keter-class containment breaches, and notifies them that communications will be down for the foreseeable future. The email tells them to evacuate as many civilians as possible by any method.</p>
<p>They both announce this to the Site through a memo, and discussions abound. Someone comes up with the idea to use the Paradise gateway to evacuate the civilians, and the argument between the two protagonists begins. Big ethical discussions (through emails and the like) and the protagonists have a falling-out. The protagonist who doesn't want to use the gateway (PrA) has flashes of the Site overrun by plants (initially dismissed as stress, but actually caused by a partial immunity to the hallucinogen), and instead of going away, the flashes become more frequent. This causes PrA to become incredibly suspicious, yet when they try to convince their friend (PrB), their claims are once again dismissed.</p>
<p>When both PrA and PrB see dark clouds on the horizon (both metaphorically and literally) tensions rise tremendously, and as PrA desperately tries to convince PrB that there is something wrong about all of this, PrB and the rest of the Site unintentionally gaslight PrA and convince them that they are suffering from prolonged stress, and tell them to have a rest (or something like that).</p>
<p>Soon after, PrB announces to the population near the beach the Foundation's existence and how they've failed their job, and that everyone needs to come with them if they want to live. There's mass panic obviously, but everyone is rallied together (meanwhile, the [hallucinated] dark clouds on the horizon are getting closer). PrA meets PrB on the beach after they've evacuated everyone (population is about ~95000) and the stuff in the 'Big Reveal' section above happens (except that PrA escapes instead of dying).</p>
<p>After this has been documented, there is an updated version of the file that appears, along with all the changes that have occurred to the anomaly.</p>
<hr /></div>
</div>
</div>
<br />
To sum up, the Paradise used small organisms loaded with hallucinogenic toxins to overtake the Site overlooking it and manipulate everyone into <em>thinking</em> the world was ending, when in fact it wasn't, thus causing them to evacuate everyone into the gateway. This way, there is still ethical friction between the protagonists, but hopefully it isn't contrived as the other disaster.
<p>TL;DR - Trippy plants from another dimension play the Foundation like a piano.</p>
<p>Anyway thanks for reading, and I hope this response suffices!</p>

							</div>

								
